'''Brain painting''' is a non-invasive [[P300 (neuroscience)|P300]]-based [[brain-computer interface]] (BCI)<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Fazel-Rezai|first1=Reza|last2=Allison|first2=Brendan Z.|last3=Guger|first3=Christoph|last4=Sellers|first4=Eric W.|last5=Kleih|first5=Sonja C.|last6=Kübler|first6=Andrea|title=P300 brain computer interface: current challenges and emerging trends|journal=Frontiers in Neuroengineering|volume=5|doi=10.3389/fneng.2012.00014}}</ref> that allows painting without the use of muscular activity. The technology combines [[electroencephalography]], signal processing algorithms and visual stimulation on a monitor to detect where the user focuses his attention, allowing him to voluntarily trigger commands to a painting software. The research project aims at assisting people afflicted with the [[Locked-in syndrome]] due to neurological or neuromuscular disease (e.g. [[Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis]] ALS), who are severely restricted in communication with their environment, and therefore cut off from the possibility of creative expression.
==History== Brain painting was co-developed by Andrea Kübler from the University of Würzburg (Germany) and Adi Hoesle. After development and testing, Brain Painting first appeared in 2010 to general press<ref>{{cite web|last1=Isabelle|first1=Bareither|title=Malen mit Gedanken: Hirn an Rechner, bitte mehr Blau!|url=http://www.spiegel.de/wissenschaft/mensch/malen-mit-gedanken-hirn-an-rechner-bitte-mehr-blau-a-726767-2.html|website=Spiegel Online|date=18 November 2010}}</ref> and to scientific press with a report of evaluation on healthy and locked-in participants<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Münßinger|first1=Jana I.|last2=Halder|first2=Sebastian|last3=Kleih|first3=Sonja C.|last4=Furdea|first4=Adrian|last5=Raco|first5=Valerio|last6=Hösle|first6=Adi|last7=Kübler|first7=Andrea|title=Brain Painting: First Evaluation of a New Brain–Computer Interface Application with ALS-Patients and Healthy Volunteers|journal=Frontiers in Neuroscience|volume=4|doi=10.3389/fnins.2010.00182}}</ref>
Supported since 2012 by the EU project "BackHome" (FP7-ICT-288566),<ref>{{cite web|last1=Maria|first1=Sanchez|title=BackHome: technological assistance in the transition from hospital to home for patients with severe disabilities|url=http://ec.europa.eu/digital-agenda/en/blog/backhome-technological-assistance-transition-hospital-home-patients-severe-disabilities-0|website=Digital Agenda for Europe, European Commission, Blog}}</ref> the BCI has been adapted for independent home use, and installed at locked-in artist's home: Heide Pfützner in 2012<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lena|first1=Stallmach|title=Kommunizieren mit Gehirn-Computer-Schnittstellen Wenn Geistesblitze den digitalen Pinsel führen|url=http://www.nzz.ch/wissen/wissenschaft/einen-computer-durch-hirnstroeme-bedienen-1.18117611|website=Neue Zürcher Zeitung|date=2013-07-17<!--, 06:00-->}}</ref> and Jürgen Thiele in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|author1=GIP-Team|title=Brain Painting: Die Kunst im Kopf|url=http://www.gip-intensivpflege.de/brainpainting/|website=GIP Intensivpflege|date=2014-02-21}}</ref> Long-term evaluation by a locked-in end user showed good satisfaction towards the system.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Holz|first1=Elisa M.|last2=Botrel|first2=Loic|last3=Kübler|first3=Andrea|title=Proceedings of TOBI Workshop I|date=2013|pages=35–36|chapter=Bridging gaps: long-term independent BCI home-use by a locked-in end-user}}</ref> After successful crowdfunding support,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Heide|first1=Pfützner|title=Brain on Fire - Mein Hirn Brennt|url=https://www.startnext.de/en/mein-hirn-brennt|website=Startnext.com}}</ref> the artist Heide Pfüztner had an exhibition in summer 2013 in Easdale, Scotland,<ref>{{cite web|title=Heide Pfuetzner: Exhibition opening - Brain on Fire|url=http://www.easdale.org/hall/viewevent.php?id=396|website=Easdale Island Hall|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140827214736/http://www.easdale.org/hall/viewevent.php?id=396|archivedate=2014-08-27|df=}}</ref> and from July to December 2014 in Würzburg (Germany)<ref>{{cite web|title=Sonntagsfrühstück für die Seele|url=http://www.uni-wuerzburg.de/sonstiges/meldungen/einblick_vorschau/single/artikel/sonntagsfr/|website=einBLICK|author1=Online-Magazin der Universität Würzburg}}</ref>
